      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Economic models are inherently abstract and often fail to capture the very real human cost of industrial decline. While efficiency metrics are mathematically sound, they do not account for community collapse and social stability, which are crucial components of a healthy nation. Therefore, a policy that preserves vital local economies and maintains social cohesion, even if it means slightly higher prices, is a morally and practically superior outcome for a functioning society. The long-term health of a country must be measured by more than just GDP figures.",
      "source": "target",
